      <body>
         <div type="edition"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:lang="grc"
              subtype="transcription"
              xml:id="zoor0270.transcription"
              corresp="#zoor0270.translation">
            <p>+<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Μνημῖον</sic>
                  <corr>Μνημεῖον</corr>
               </choice>
               <lb/> Μιλίχου<lb/> Ἀβδάλγου,<lb/>
                    ἀποθανὼν<lb/> ἐτῶν κηʹ.<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Θάρσι</sic>
                  <corr>Θάρσει</corr>
               </choice>, <choice>
                  <sic>οὐδὶ<lb/>ς</sic>
                  <corr>οὐδείς</corr>
               </choice>
               <choice>
                  <abbr>ἀ<unclear>θ</unclear>άνατ</abbr>
                  <expan>ἀθάνατος</expan>
               </choice>
               <lb/>. +</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0270.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0270.transcription">
            <p>Monument of Milichos, (son) of Abdalges, who died (at the age) of 28 years. Be of
                    good cheer, no one (is) immortal.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>No date is provided in the inscription, but it has been dated to the second half of the fourth century CE on the strength of other factors. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. The tombstone is rectangular, and curved at its upper right corner, with some breaking and chipping. The inscribed surface is smoothed to two different levels and has suffered flaking and damage, resulting in a loss of text. A simple cross is engraved above and below the inscription, with the latter almost worn away. The text is also engraved. The author notes that the names in this inscription also appear elsewhere at Ghor es-Safi. The text contains spelling and grammatical errors.</p>
         </div>
